              <h2>How this diet plan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This diet plan calculator combines evidence-based calorie
                equations with flexible macro presets and a simple food database
                to build a realistic daily meal plan. It is designed to be more
                practical than a basic calorie calculator, but less overwhelming
                than full tracking apps.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Estimating your calorie needs (BMR &amp; TDEE)</h3>
              <p>
                First, the tool estimates your
                <strong>Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR)</strong> – the calories your
                body burns at rest – and then multiplies it by an activity
                factor to get your
                <strong>Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE)</strong>.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Mifflin–St Jeor equation (default)
                </p>
                <p>
                  For men: \( \text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight}_{kg} + 6.25
                  \times \text{height}_{cm} - 5 \times \text{age} + 5 \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  For women: \( \text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight}_{kg} + 6.25
                  \times \text{height}_{cm} - 5 \times \text{age} - 161 \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold">
                  Katch–McArdle (used when body fat % is provided)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{BMR} = 370 + 21.6 \times \text{Lean Mass}_{kg} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  where \( \text{Lean Mass} = \text{weight}_{kg} \times (1 -
                  \text{body fat fraction}) \).
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Your TDEE is then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \( \text{TDEE} = \text{BMR} \times \text{activity factor} \)
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Sedentary: 1.2</li>
                  <li>Lightly active: 1.375</li>
                  <li>Moderately active: 1.55</li>
                  <li>Very active: 1.725</li>
                  <li>Athlete: 1.9</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Applying your goal (deficit or surplus)</h3>
              <p>
                Next, the calculator adjusts calories up or down depending on
                your goal:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weight loss</strong>: typically 10–25% below TDEE.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Maintenance</strong>: around 100% of TDEE.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weight gain</strong>: usually 10–20% above TDEE.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These ranges are moderate and meant for most generally healthy
                adults. More aggressive approaches should be supervised by a
                professional.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Macro distribution</h3>
              <p>
                Calories are split into protein, carbohydrates, and fat
                according to the macro pattern you choose. Each macro has a
                specific calorie value:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul>
                  <li>Protein: 4 kcal per gram</li>
                  <li>Carbohydrates: 4 kcal per gram</li>
                  <li>Fat: 9 kcal per gram</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  Example: if your target is 2,000 kcal with 30% protein, 40%
                  carbs, 30% fat:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Protein kcal = 0.30 × 2000 = 600 → 600 / 4 = 150 g</li>
                  <li>Carb kcal = 0.40 × 2000 = 800 → 800 / 4 = 200 g</li>
                  <li>Fat kcal = 0.30 × 2000 = 600 → 600 / 9 ≈ 67 g</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Splitting across meals</h3>
              <p>
                Finally, the calculator divides your daily calories and macros
                across your chosen number of meals and snacks. Main meals get a
                larger share; snacks get a smaller share. This is only a
                starting template – you can shift calories between meals to
                match your appetite and schedule.
              </p>

              <h2>Interpreting your diet plan</h2>
              <h3>Daily calorie target</h3>
              <p>
                Use the daily calorie number as a
                <strong>starting estimate</strong>. Track your weight trend over
                2–4 weeks:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If you are losing weight faster than expected and feel low
                  energy, consider increasing calories slightly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If your weight is not changing, adjust by 100–200 kcal/day and
                  re-check after another 2–3 weeks.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Protein, carbs, and fat</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Protein</strong> supports muscle maintenance, satiety,
                  and recovery. Many people do well with 1.6–2.2 g/kg of body
                  weight when dieting or strength training.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Carbohydrates</strong> fuel training and daily
                  activity. Very low-carb approaches can work for some but are
                  not necessary for fat loss.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fat</strong> is essential for hormones and nutrient
                  absorption. Extremely low-fat diets are usually not advisable
                  long term.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Sample meal plan vs. real life</h3>
              <p>
                The sample meal plan uses generic foods (like oats, chicken,
                beans, tofu, olive oil, fruit, and vegetables) to demonstrate
                how to hit your targets. You can:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Swap foods for culturally appropriate equivalents.</li>
                <li>
                  Adjust portion sizes while keeping an eye on total calories
                  and macros.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Batch-cook a few core meals and rotate them through the week.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Safety, limitations, and when to seek help</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is for
                <strong>informational and educational purposes only</strong>. It
                does not diagnose, treat, or cure any condition and is not a
                substitute for professional medical advice.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>Talk to your doctor or a registered dietitian</strong>
                before using this tool to guide major diet changes if you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Have diabetes, kidney disease, heart disease, digestive
                  disorders, or other chronic conditions.
                </li>
                <li>Are pregnant, breastfeeding, under 18, or over 65.</li>
                <li>
                  Have a history of eating disorders or disordered eating.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Take medications that interact with food or body weight.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you notice dizziness, extreme fatigue, hair loss, menstrual
                changes, or other worrying symptoms while dieting, stop
                aggressive dieting and seek medical advice.
              </p>
